<TEXT>
for years philadelphia schools have offered students a chance 
to study latin as early as fourth grade but this fall fewer kids 
will learn their amo amas amats a tight budget has forced 
the layoff of six out of 26 itinerant latin teachers 
an awful lot of them wont even finish high school and the 
only language they are exposed to is street language this is the 
one opportunity they have to get a little something beyond 
thatsaid one laidoff latin teacher h michael dunn 
many such cuts affecting both innovative programs and 
daytoday operations await bigcity districts across the country 
this fall a check by the associated press found that districts 
from philadelphia boston and new york to dade county fla and 
los angeles face the worst fiscal problems since the mid70s 
its going to be tough to innovate when youre trying to 
survive said james fleming associate superintendent of dade 
county schools a district that gained national notice for school 
reforms but now faces a 108 million deficit that will likely lead 
to more crowded classes 
with a possible recession looming and worsening state finances 
putting a squeeze on school budgets bigcity school officials 
everywhere are bracing for teacher hiring freezes layoffs and 
larger classes 
its a very bleak fall said jewell gould research director 
of the american federation of teachers 
he and others believe next spring could bring even worse news 
when districts customarily send out layoff notices 
one leading reformer called this falls cutbacks fresh evidence 
that political leaders give more lip service than resources to 
school improvement 
if snow is piling up in city streets you get a greater sense 
of emergency than if half the kids drop out of school year after 
year said ernest l boyer president of the carnegie foundation 
for the advancement of teaching 
on the one hand we say education is at the center of what we 
hope for and dream about and we almost get maudlin about it but 
then if something happens it gets put off as kid stuff he 
said 
this is easily the worst fiscal crisis i have seen in the last 
20 years said fleming of dade county 
state funding fell 44 million less than expected said dade 
county school spokesman andy gollan its already meant elimination 
of a merit schools program where schools devised innovative 
programs to help students achieve educational goals 
philadelphia anticipating deficits of 68 million for fiscal 
year 199192 170 million in 1993 and 275 million in 1994 has 
put on hold reforms including fullday kindergartens lengthening 
the school day and year and more classroom computers 
its come to a period where we have to make hard choices 
which are not necessarily popular choices said leontine d 
scott associate superintendent 
in boston a 397 million budget approved last week is 64 
million lower than last years cuts include 100 fewer nontenured 
teachers fewer school police reduced extracurricular and 
afterschool programs less funding for a cityfinanced parent 
organization and reductions in a private industry council that 
provides jobs for highschool students 
the citys schoolchildren are treated like secondclass 
citizens because they dont have the political clout that other 
communities have said boston school committee member peggy davis 
mullen 
in los angeles a 220 million budget gap earlier this year 
forced extensive administrative cuts the crisis worsened last week 
when gov george deukmejian announced he was withholding 465 
million in school funds statewide compelling the district to cut 
77 million more from the 199091 budget 
school officials havent decided yet how to parcel out the cuts 
but a number of reform ideas have already been shelved or reduced 
a bilingual master plan designed to help nonenglish speaking 
students in all major subject areas has been only partially funded 
the district is also postponing expansion of its schoolbased 
management program in which more than 60 schools participate 
devastating would not be too strong a word said school 
board member rita walters it just socks it to us 
new york citys school board must come up with 268 million in 
instructional cuts this fall after having already eliminated some 
350 jobs at the central board 
how that will be done is the unanswered question said susan 
amlung a spokeswoman for the united federation of teachers 
the district is likely to cut school aides and 
paraprofessionals measures that the union fears will put more 
students in alreadyovercrowded classes school officials insist 
that wont happen kindergarten classes currently average 248 
pupils and highschool classes of 40 or more are not uncommon 
seattles 2436 million school budget has meant eliminating 165 
teaching administrative and other positions mainly through 
attrition 
its been a difficult time said seattle schools budget 
manager george steinhofer weve taken a number of reductions in 
central administration and this year we took reductions in special 
education and bilingual programs the only place left to look is in 
basic educational programs 
new orleans is closing two of its three centers for problem 
students and 60 school employees were laid off to balance the 358 
million budget said superintendent everett williams 
thats been the story of our life in this school district for 
the past four or five years i have had no budget thats been an 
even budget where i have been able to start off the year with no 
cuts at all he said 
in houston superintendent joan raymond is pushing for a record 
18 percent tax rate hike to fund a 7979 million budget the 
proposed budget would provide a 10 percent pay raise for teachers 
31 new principals and deans a dropout prevention program beefed 
up security a principal performance incentive program and funding 
of a massive construction program 
but some taxpayers are resisting 
by no extent of the imagination is the public going along with 
this said john pellicciotti a board member of the taxpayers 
coalition of greater houston 
not all cities are in such dire straits 
in atlanta public schools comptroller lawrence thompson said 
the district has not had cuts next years budget is 3313 
million compared with 3193 million this past school year 
weve been pretty fortunate thompson said 
newark with a 421 million school budget has an 85 million 
shortfall but has largely avoided layoffs some assistant 
principals and other administrators may be demoted to save money 
said spokesman kirk smith 
next year the district will get as much as 50 million in 
additional funds as part of a state plan to boost the quality of 
new jersey city schools but another state plan to shift teacher 
pension costs entirely to local districts could cancel out those 
gains smith said 
in detroit an 889 million budget for the 199091 school year 
includes such reform initiatives as expanded preschools and special 
schools meant to help troubled ninthgraders avoid disciplinary 
problems 
a 5mill property tax increase and a bond issue approved by 
voters last september wiped out the districts 160 million deficit 
</TEXT>
