<TEXT>
here are excerpts from editorials on the middle east crisis in 
sunday editions of us newspapers 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the mideast crisis triggered by the decision of militaristic 
iraq to seize one oilproducing nation and threaten the conquest of 
others has predictably destabilized the worlds energy network 
what is surprising and inexcusable is that america enters 
this state of confusion without an energy policy any more 
comprehensive than the hapless policies of 1973 the iraqi threat 
to one of the worlds major oilproducing regions should force the 
development of an energy policy designed to secure the nations 
energy needs a national energy policy is long overdue 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
faster than anyone had bargained for america is learning what 
it will take to defend its national interests in the postcold war 
era neither hawks nor doves of the old school are enjoying the 
lesson 
one lesson of kuwait is that the united states must maintain 
enough military strength to protect its commerce and citizens from 
pirates like hussein this is a depressing prospect for doves who 
have been gleefully preparing to cut americas defense budget 
middle east events havent been kind to cold war hawks either 
 
european armies mirved missiles and 800 million bombers arent 
much use against the likes of hussein the crises america is likely 
to face in the foreseeable future will demand strong airborne and 
marine forces light armor tactical air and naval power much of 
it able to move on a days notice to any trouble spot in the world 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
saddam wants to be seen as a military strongman who gets what he 
needs through brute strength he sees hostagetakingy correctly 
as the desperate resort of the powerless and not worthy of the 
selfproclaimed leader of the arab world 
not yet that is if they are not actual hostages the foreign 
nationals held by iraq represent insurance for saddam they are his 
rainyday fund so to speak if and when his situation 
deteriorates which it will they will become far more valuable 
they will become in truth hostages 
it is the rule of the middle east bazaar any americans held 
hostage by iraq become worth what we are willing to pay the more 
preoccupied we become with getting them back the more unlikely 
they will be released at a price we are capable of paying 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
by snatching kuwait hussein injected uncertainty into the 
worldwide oil system uncertainty affects prices because oil 
selling today has to be priced at what it will cost tomorrow to 
replace it uncertainty affects supplies because consumers from the 
motorist to the refiner to the gaspump jockey lay in extra in case 
shortages develop thereby creating supply disruptions 
whether in the persian gulf or at home bad oil news will be 
telegraphed to americans via their local gas pump they should get 
mad at themselves if they continue to let their dependence on 
imported oil make them vulnerable to madmen 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
it should be said that the arab leagues decision to send 
arab troops to defend saudi arabia is one of the more hopeful 
signs for the future of world peace since world war ii for it 
therapeutically destroys the myth of arab unity a fantasy based 
on the preposterous but powerful assumption that the various arab 
countries comprise one arab nation 
saddam has forced fellow arabs to choose between civilized 
international behavior and a bloodyminded arab dictator 
it also represents a great personal victory for president bush 
and for us efforts to create a global force to thwart iraqi 
aggression the president has spent much time and energy trying to 
ensure that the world community and not just the west condemns 
and confronts baghdad 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
theres an immediate lesson to be drawn from the confrontation 
in the persian gulf the danger of this countrys crushing 
dependence on imported oil in part thats a legacy of the reagan 
years but it is also a failure of industry and consumers to 
recognize the advantages of alternate energy sources 
there arent any quickfix solutions the fastest and cheapest 
way to respond to the cutback in oil imports would be a national 
conservation program the president in concert with the nations 
governors and mayors ought to act immediately to curb profligate 
use of petroleum 
we can no longer remain complacent about importing 50 percent of 
our petroleum this imbalance must be ended our future economic 
wellbeing is at stake 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
although us military experts grow more sanguine as each hour 
passes the wild card in this is the unpredictability of the 
volatile saddam a man who has used poison gas against the kurds in 
his own country and against teenage iranian soldiers his 
volatility makes military planning against him more difficult 
saddam can rant all he wants but he is up against 
formidable odds his whole economy is based on the iraqis ability 
to sell their oil so as long as the blockade is successful it 
amounts to an economic chokehold 
the events played out in the sands of the middle east will 
surely have repercussions on the us domestic front in terms of 
both energy and defense policies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

