<TEXT>
a rare case of diphtheria diagnosed in an 
18yearold woman prompted a warning this weekend by worried 
health officials 
most children are immunized against the potentially lethal 
disease when they begin school but they can outgrow the immunity 
said dr linda a fisher chief medical examiner of st louis 
county 
she issued a warning saturday asking adults not to overlook the 
symptoms of diphtheria which include sore throat fever cough and 
difficulty swallowing 
diphtheria features the development of a greenishgray membrane 
in the throat the membrane can block the airway causing 
respiratory failure 
the woman was listed in serious condition saturday at st johns 
mercy medical center in creve coeur fisher said she was diagnosed 
with diphtheria on friday after showing symptoms for about a week 
dr farrin manian an infectious disease specialist who is 
treating the woman said state records indicate this may be the 
first missouri diphtheria case in 15 years he said medical 
literature showed fewer than five cases in the united states in the 
last 10 years 
