<DOCNO> AP900812-0049 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
for the first time since world war i american 
troops stare across a nomans land at a potential enemy who has 
used chemical weapons and may do so again 
iraq is known to have stockpiled at least two chemical weapons 
one burns the skin like liquid fire the other kills in minutes by 
disrupting nervous system functions 
and iraqs army massed along a border across from us troops 
in saudi arabia is known to have used at least one of the 
chemicals in its war with iran and against kurdish dissident groups 
in its own country 
iraqs burning chemical is thought to be the same mustard gas 
that confronted the greatgrandfathers of todays us troops in 
the trenches of world war i europe it worked so well 70 years ago 
that civilized nations banned the use of such weapons mustard gas 
still does its work with ghastly efficiency 
the other chemical agent commonly called nerve gas is a group 
of compounds added to the arsenals of war by advances in chemistry 
and in biological understanding it takes but a drop of 
concentrated nerve agent absorbed by the skin to kill 
both chemical weapons can be delivered by bomb artillery shell 
or mine when the ordnance explodes the chemicals vaporize 
spreading quickly 
mustard in a gas or droplet form is readily absorbed by 
exposed skin and is quickly taken up by inner layers of tissue 
initially there are no symptoms says lloyd roberts a 
research administrator at the armys institute of chemical defense 
there is a delayed effect 
reactions vary depending on concentrations and individuals said 
roberts but generally within one to six hours a victim will 
experience itching and reddening of the skin within 12 hours huge 
blisters appear the blisters burst and the skin is sloughed 
leaving large gaping wounds ripe for infection 
it is very much like a third degree burn said roberts and 
thats how we treat it 
dead skin must be pulled away and the wound washed with sterile 
solution healing is slow and painful infection a constant threat 
the eyes are the most vulnerable to mustard said roberts 
even a medium exposure causes pain and swelling and the white of 
the eye turns an angry red in heavy exposures there are severe 
lacerations of the cornea some soldiers in world war i were 
blinded 
but mustard does its worst damage in the respiratory system 
it tends to be lethal only when inhaled roberts said 
just as it blisters the skin inhaled mustard gas blisters the 
lungs and the airway of the respiratory tract breathing becomes 
tortured patients cough blood internal surface tissue dies and 
pneumonia becomes a fearful threat 
medical care depends on the symptoms 
a mild dose said roberts causes hoarseness and sore throat and 
no treatment is required for a cough the army uses syrups for 
laryngitis there is sterile steam and bed rest 
for severe cases patients are hospitalized for months and 
treated aggressively with antibiotics to ward off pneumonia 
mortality from mustard gas in world war i was about one 
percent said roberts now with modern care it could be even 
less 
unlike mustard that can cause large obvious wounds nerve 
agents are sly quick killers attacking the body at the molecular 
level 
readily absorbed by the skin nerve gas goes to work 
immediately it kills by disrupting a chemical reaction that occurs 
each time a muscle moves 
roberts said nerve agents bind to a protein molecule called 
acetyclcholinesterase of ache and keep it from doing its job 
ache normally destroys another protein molecule called 
acetylcholine or ach this molecule is a neurotransmitter that 
moves from nerve to muscle each time a voluntary muscle operates 
it also works in the brain to carry signals from cell to cell 
normally when the neurotransmitter has done its job it is 
immediately inactivated by ache but if the nerve gas keeps the 
ache from working then the neurotransmitter builds up and 
continues to act on the muscles and brain cells 
muscle control is lost spasms set in as muscles contract time 
after time theres weakness and collapse respiration is 
depressed heart beat slows convulsions unconsciousness the 
diaphragm muscle stops working death 
the person suffocates said roberts unprotected a person 
is dead within 10 minutes tops 
as with any chemical weapon the effects depend on the 
concentration after a weak exposure symptoms can be mild and pass 
within hours a stronger nonlethal concentration may cause 
symptoms that last a day or longer but there are seldom longterm 
effects said roberts 
with a nerve agent if you survive you can return to duty 
within a week he said it either kills you or you recover 
one way to modify or even completely block the nerve gas effect 
is with a chemical antidote 
and roberts said american troops are issued two of these one is 
atropine and the other is called pralidoxime choride the drugs are 
carried in springloaded syringes 
at the first sign of exposure a soldier can slap the syringe 
against a thigh and the drugs quickly enter the body 
both atropine and pralidoxime choride said roberts work by 
inhibiting the excess ach neurotransmitter molecule in effect the 
drugs for a brief time do the job of the acetylcholinesterase that 
was attacked by the nerve gas 
the first line of defense against a chemical attack though are 
protective garments boots rubber gloves masks and hooded helmets 
on the battlefield of chemical warfare survival means every 
inch of skin must be covered and every breath filtered even in an 
arabian desert where midday temperatures may soar to 110 degrees 
</TEXT>
