<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of kuwait forced economists to 
reevaluate their projections but left many even more convinced 
that the us economy is weakening while also facing the 
possibility of higher inflation 
developments in the weeks preceding the iraqi invasion already 
had economists warning of higher inflation and weaker economic 
growth 
in a sense the oil price increase only reinforces what was 
happening before said alan levenson an economist at the wefa 
group a balacynwyd pa economic forecasting firm 
weve been through oil shocks before now we have to make some 
judgments about where the dust will settle this time he said 
one key to the economys direction is how the federal reserve 
will act as a matter of policy the fed doesnt disclose its 
intentions but it has enormous power to influence economic growth 
through two principal means controlling the supply of money in the 
banking system and adjusting rates banks pay to borrow 
the spotlight on what the central banks strategy might be has 
brightened because of events in the middle east 
before the iraqi invasion there were signs of economic weakness 
which suggested the fed would move to ease credit 
julys unemployment figures showed the jobless rate reaching a 
2year high julys purchasing managers index slipped below 50 
indicating that the manufacturing sector might be in decline and 
the feds own regional survey showed economic growth was slowing 
wholesale prices in july edged down 01 percent the government 
said friday but analysts said the figures may indicate the last 
respite from inflation before the effects of soaring oil costs 
linked to the mideast crisis are felt 
the fed is faced with the same choices it had before the oil 
price increase how much should it ease the money supply to offset 
economic weakness but avoid increasing the potential for inflation 
the weakening economy and higher inflation put the fed in a 
common but no less troublesome predicament on how to deal with 
interest rates 
increasing the supply of money in the economy would lower 
interest rates and spur more spending possibly giving the economy 
a dose of vitality however with more money floating around 
inflation could accelerate prices may already be pulled upward 
across the economy by the increase in oil 
holding back on the money supply however could spur higher 
interest rates and make it more difficult to buy new cars and homes 
and build new factories irwin kellner chief economist at 
manufacturers hanover trust co said fears of inflation are 
exaggerated higher gasoline prices wont remain after the summer 
peak driving season ends labor day he said with less consumer 
demand it will be even more difficult for oil companies to pass 
along higher wholesale costs he said 
its been our assertion for some time now that the us 
economy entered into a recession in the second quarter kellner 
said 
assuming the middle east situation settles down kellner said he 
expects the fed to loosen the money supply after its policymaking 
federal open market committee meets aug 21 
if it hadnt been for the invasion we would have seen easing 
already kellner said 
the big question is will it stick or not no were not going 
to return to 20 a barrel anytime soon but will there be some 
decreases ray stone of stone amp mccarthy research associates 
inc said 
the higher oil prices makes it harder for the fed to ease 
the money supply now he said 
</TEXT>
